@784  = ~Aquamarine Ioun Stone~
@785  = ~This ioun stone glows with a distingushed aquamarine hue. Its name comes from blue to slightly greenish blue hues of seawater and it was said to calm waves and keep sailors safe at sea. Like many other ioun stones, the aquamarine ioun stones grants essential protections to its wielder.

STATISTICS

Equipped Abilities:
 Armor Class Bonus: +3
 Saving Throws: +3
 Magic Resistance Bonus: +10%
 Complete Mind Shield
  (Immunity to any mind-alterating effects)

Special:  Protects Against Critical Hits
Weight: 2~
@786  = ~A massive horn of beaten lead, wound with brazen chains. The horn is horribly mangled, as if some tremendous force had crushed it. Jagged blades protrude along its length, almost as if it were meant to be used as club by some gigantic creature, as well as a battle-horn. A placard mounted beneath the horn reads ‘Cleansing Horn of Acheron.‘~
@787  = ~A brilliant ruby statuette stands on this pedestal, carved into the image of a winged humanoid. The figure is either demonic or angelic in nature... but it is difficult to tell which, because it refracts the light in the galleria strangely. There is no placard indicated what, exactly, the statuette is.~
@788  = ~An animated, bloody iron chain, coiling and uncoiling upon itself. The chain itself is slightly warm to the touch, as if it were alive, and seems to bend and weave like the spine of a snake. You notice that various barbs, tiny hooks, needles and other small, sharp bits are welded along the chain‘s length. A small placard reads: ‘A kyton‘s animate chain, from Jangling Hiter.‘~
@789  = ~This painting, an abstract work of greens and purples, writhes and ripples as it‘s watched. Closer examination reveals that the actual painted image is changing, rather the canvas itself. A placard states ‘Moment‘s Glance from the Walls of Moch‘chma.‘~
@790  = ~The surface of this painting... a wild collage of vivid colors... ripples constantly, as if it were the surface of a pond during a light rain. A placard reads "Wave Motion Study #7."~
@791  = ~A set of four paintings which portray an empty beach in the dead of night. The surface of the painting smells faintly of sea air, and the painted sea seems to ebb and flow across the darkened shore. A placard reads ‘Karasuthran Shoreline.‘~
@792  = ~A painting of tall, black cliffs against a blood-red sky. There looks to be figures hiding amongst the crags of the cliffs but, whenever you squint at the painting to try and make them out, the images fade into nothing. A placard reads ‘Outland Raiders.‘~
@793  = ~This painting shows what looks to be an infinitely long stream of bilious green gas, stretching off into darkness. The horizon of a blasted, rocky plain can be seen in the lower right-hand corner of the painting... one is given the impression that the ‘head‘ of the green cloud is rearing to strike down upon it. A placard reads ‘Hazazoth at the Consumption of N‘gar.‘~
@794  = ~This painting depicts a shore-scene, with a wide, reddish-orange sun setting behind a peninsula or large jetty. The scene, though unoriginal, is breathtaking - the play of the fading daylight across the water is captured perfectly - but staring at the painted sun for any length of time makes your eyes ache. A placard reads ‘Surface of Thalasia.‘~
@795  = ~This painting shows an enormous granite keep - a hideous thing, long and low, covered in leering gargoyles - suspended in what looks to be the night sky. A cloud of crimson and violet vapor whirls in the background along the right side of the painting. A placard reads simply ‘The Library.‘~
@796  = ~This painting is a dark cityscape, a far-away view of some giant center of civilization being burned to the ground. The streets of the place are empty, however, absent of soldiers, refugees, and even corpses. A placard reads ‘The Folly of Udo.‘~
@797  = ~This looks to be a subterranean landscape... a massive cavern interior filled with colorful, faintly luminescent, gigantic fungi. A placard reads ‘Vale Beneath Clanggedin.‘~
@798  = ~This is a portrait of a grotesque, hook-nosed old crone. The hag‘s flesh is a sickly blue-gray color; her eyes glow red like the embers of a dying fire. Her chin, long and sharp, juts forward in an extreme under-bite; two yellowed canines protrude upwards from her lower jaw, like small tusks. The smile upon her withered, purplish lips speaks of a horrible secret. A placard reads ‘Gray Hag of Oinos.‘~
@799  = ~Several shards of black crystal - or ice - swirl within the freezing wind that this ornate pedestal gives forth. Each shard looks razor sharp; touching or grabbing one could be perilous. A placard on the pedestal reads ‘Dark Birds of Ocanthus.‘~
@800  = ~This staircase is blocked from the other side. You will have to find another route up.~
@801  = ~This is a beautiful silver mirror.~
@802  = ~This is a solid crystal tank, with several fish frozen inside.~
@803  = ~These shelves are stocked with various and sundry items ranging from books and magical trinkets to dry plants and insects, parchment, food, and cookware. Rows of human skulls have been neatly arranged upon these shelves.~
@804  = ~Spiritual Hammer~
@805  = ~Spiritual Hammer (Invocation)  
Range: Self 
Duration: 3 rounds + 1 round/level 
Casting Time: 5 
Area of Effect: Special 
Saving Throw: None 

By calling upon his deity, the caster of a spiritual hammer spell brings into existence a magical hammer. For the duration of the spell, the Priest may use the magic weapon without non-proficiency penalties. It strikes as a magical weapon with a bonus of +1 for every six experience levels (or fraction) of the spellcaster, up to a total of +6 enchantment level, +6 to the attack roll and +6 to the damage roll for a 13th-level caster. The base damage inflicted when it scores a hit is 2d4 + 3 vs. opponents plus the magical bonus.~
@806  = ~Tempus Will~
@807  = ~Tempus Will (Evocation) 
Range: None
Duration: 1 round/level
Casting Time: 6
Area of Effect: Caster
Saving Throw: None

Through this spell, the caster imbues himself with the strength and skill of a fighter of the same level. The priest’s strength is set to 18/00, even if it is normally higher, his THAC0 becomes that of a fighter of the same level, and he gains 1 temporary hit point for every level he has attained. This will last for the duration of the spell or until successfully dispelled. Multiple castings of this spell are not cumulative.~
@808  = ~Tempus Shield~
@809  = ~Tempus Shield (Alteration) 
Sphere: Numbers
Range: 30 yards
Duration: 9 rounds
Casting Time: 6
Area of Effect: Special
Saving Throw: None

This spell causes a localized folding of space. The folded space takes the form of an invisible disk that protects the caster. Any missile weapon that intersects this disk is instantaneously reversed in direction. Melee factors such as speed, range, and damage are unaffected; the direction of the object or force is simply rotated through a 180 degree arc. The sender of the missile finds himself the target of his own attack. The caster of the mirror may direct missile attacks normally through the space occupied by the mirror.~
@810  = ~Iron Skins~
@811  = ~Iron Skins (Alteration) 
Range: 0
Duration: 12 hours
Casting Time: 1 round
Area of Effect: Caster
Saving Throw: None 

When Accalia casts this powerful spell upon herself, an outer skin of iron will move up from the ground completely covering her. This skin is, of course, magical and will hinder her in no way. The effect of this is to protect the caster from physical attacks such as melee weapons and projectiles. For every two levels of the caster, an additional skin is gained upon casting. The skins will remain until she is affected by a dispel magic, all of the skins are removed due to physical attacks or the spell duration expires. It is important to note that this will not protect Accalia from any area attacks such as fireball, however it will protect her from physical magical attacks such as magic missile.~
@812  = ~battle priest of tempus~
@813  = ~Battle Priest of Tempus~
@814  = ~This kit was created especially for Accalia. Tempus is the Realms’ God of War, the Lord of Battle, the Foehammer. He is random in his favors, yet his chaotic nature favors all sides equally. He may be on an army’s side on one day and against them the next. Such is the nature of war as embodied by Tempus.

The dress of the priest of Tempus is armor, battle-worn and battered. In more civilized regions this has been replaced by a steel skullcap, but the message is the same--these are warrior priests. Their place is in the trenches with the troops, urging them onwards. Priests of Tempus may be found on both sides of a conflict, as none can ever truly know who the war god will favor.

Abilities:

- ‘Spiritual Hammer‘ (thrice per day), the magic weapon without non-proficiency penalties strikes with a bonus of +2 for every six experience levels (or fraction) of the spellcaster, up to a total of +6 enchantment level, +6 to the attack roll and +6 to the damage roll for a 13th-level caster, the base damage inflicted when it scores a hit is 2d4 + 3 vs. opponents plus the magical bonus.
- ‘Tempus Will‘ (twice per day) imbues the caster with the strength and skill of a fighter of the same level, so the priest’s strength is set to 18/00, even if it is normally higher, his THAC0 becomes that of a fighter of the same level, and he gains 1 temporary hit point for every level he has attained.
- ‘Tempus Shield‘ (twice per day) creates an invisible rotating through a 180 degree arc disk that protects the caster in a way that any missile weapon that intersects this disk is instantaneously reversed in direction.
- ‘Iron Skin‘ (once a day), the magical outer skin of iron moves up from the ground completely covering Accalia without hindering her in any way, protecting from physical attacks such as melee weapons and projectiles. Accalia gains an additional skin for every two levels, and for each skin she possesses, the spell will stop one attack.
- ‘False Dawn‘(thrice per day) calls into existence a bright reddish light, as if a sunrise were occurring, affecting all undead creatures within the area of effect so they suffer 6d6 points of damage and act confused on the round with no saving throw against this damage.
-  Can only be of True Neutral, or any Chaotic alignments.~
@815  = ~Holy Shield of Tempus~
@816  = ~This is a medium-size shield with a number of wicked barbs protruding from its surface. A flaming sword, the holy symbol of Tempus, has been etched into the center of the shield. The inscription upon its stand reads:  "The Shield of Maergeth of the Order of the Steel Fang, slain on the eleventh day of the Battle at Boareskyr Bridge."

STATISTICS:

+3 to Armour Class
+3 to Strength
10% Magic Resistance while worn
Grants two additional 5th and 6th level spells.

Usable by:
Accalia~
@817  = ~Accalia~
@818  = ~When first you set eyes on Accalia you are taken aback by her likeness to Branwen, a young cleric and  also a priest of Tempus, that you rescued from a stony existence at Nashkiel fair. She has the same pale coloured hair and speaks with same accent as Branwen.... but that was another time and sense tells you that this is not the same woman. Originally from Neverwinter, Accalia will tell you that she was sent to Easthaven to aid Battlelord Everard after the death of  Warpriest Renfeld who was killed in a confrontation with barbarians near Bryn Shander. She tells you of her duties to assist Everard in the armoury and in the performing of rituals. Accalia is happy to tell you of any of these rituals and local battle lore, but when you ask her to tell of the battle of Gerard‘s Stone, she will tell you to ask Everard as he prefers to tell of it himself. Accalia will say that she is content to do the will of Tempus in the temple but would much prefer to be on the front line, protecting the *immigrants*, (a term Accalia uses when she refers to herself and the townsfolk of Easthaven), from the spontaneous attacks from the many barbarian tribes in the area.~
@819  = ~Hammer of Tempus + 3~
@820  = ~Not much is known about the origin of this war hammer, except that Tempus grants it himself to the most faithful of his followers. The holy symbol of Tempus is engraved on the head of this hammer, granting even greater powers to its wielder.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Abilities:
   Immunity to Fear and Panic
  
Combat Abilities:
   -1 to AC and THAC0 to an opponent with each hit (no save)
   Damage to Undead: 4D4 +10
        (saving throw vs. death (-4 penalty) or be utterly destroyed)
   
THAC0: +3 bonus
Damage:  2D4 + 3
Damage type:  crushing
Weight: 4
Speed Factor: 2
Proficiency Type: Warhammer
Type:  1-handed

Usable by:
Accalia~
@821  = ~Your dreams were of being chased down by a pack of werewolves. You waken before the pack rips you to pieces, only to find the flesh werewolves hungry for your blood.~
@822  = ~Melora~
@854  = ~Melora hates men and magic and is quick to tell you so if you happen to be male or adept in the arts of sorcery. Melora’s small Hafling eyes will look at you with even more contempt and her Sturdy Hafling body will take on a stance of defiance as she speaks to you if you happen to be both male and mage! The illegitimate daughter of a mage and a hafling servant girl, Melora’s first years were hapless. Despised by a father that regarded as an “accident” and who treated her like some lesser being, Melora did not even have the comfort of a mother’s love. She too cast Melora aside when she made a wealthy marriage for herself. So perhaps her hatred is justified, or so Melora would have you believe. The young maiden swore to herself that she would ever be on the side of the oppressed. She has become somewhat of a hero to the poorer people on the outskirts of Candlekeep for her generosity with rich men’s money, none of which she keeps for herself. Often widows and poorer families have found their incomes supplemented by her generous nature. None will speak ill of her excepting the authorities of course... but Melora cares very little for what they say.~
@855  = ~Ryxyr~
@856  = ~Adlonn, a famous shadow master of a thief guild, earned his place with two legendary weapons: Ryxyr and Shadow Blade. Some say without the weapons, Adlonn will be no more than the bandits in city streets. Finally, he magically enhanced the weapons to serve only their owner, and granted them to his most trusted friend. Adlonn became a normal thief then, away from his guild. No one knew where he‘d gone. Occasional tales in taverns tell that he‘s still doing what he did, steal from the rich and help the poor.

