@894  = ~Book of Wisdom (Part 1)~
@895  = ~The ancient text is yellowed and crumbling, and written in a language that is far-removed from modern-day common. Still, portions of it are translatable with effort.~
@896  = ~There is no easily recognizable structure in the book; in many parts it is difficult to discover a logical progression of thought or to discern the principles of arrangement. However, a series of six poems about the search for and attainment of wisdom divide the book into something resembling chapters, although the divisions are not thematically based. Upon browsing the first part of the book, you reveal that it is essentially a collection of ethical teachings. The teachings are applicable to all conditions of life: to parents and children, to husbands and wives, to the young, to masters, to friends, to the rich, and to the poor. Many of them are rules of courtesy and politeness; and a still greater number contain advice and instruction as to the duties of man toward himself and others, especially the poor, as well as toward society.~
@897  = ~Book of Wisdom (Part 2)~
@898  = ~The ancient text is yellowed and crumbling, and written in a language that is far-removed from modern-day common. Still, is it translatable with some effort.~
@899  = ~In the second part of the book, wisdom is taught as synonymous with the fear of the gods, and sometimes is identified with adherence to the Mosaic law. The maxims are expressed in exact formulas, and are illustrated by striking images. They show a profound knowledge of the human heart, the disillusionment of experience, a fraternal sympathy with the poor and the oppressed.~
@900  = ~Book of Wisdom (Part 3)~
@901  = ~The third part of the book contains a philosophical discussion on the basis of the moral life. The standard of good and the reason for good conduct is existing law, custom, and individual eudaemonistics. Modern social philosophies developing concurrently in Faerun, by contrast, encourage good behavior for the health of the state, families, or from fear of reprisal, while the Book of Wisdom notes that punishment may follow from poor choices, the laws should be followed because they are ordained by the gods. Wisdom is represented as the result of human reflection, and thus as the guide in all the affairs of life but predetermination of good and evil remains the gods' prerogative. The wisdom texts emphasize human powers as bestowed directly by the gods.~
